Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.71) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.18. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 12.59 (S.E. = 2.70, p < .001, 95% CI [7.29, 17.88]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.10, S.E. = 0.05, p = 0.024, 95% CI [0.01, 0.19]; Std. beta = 0.38, 95% CI [0.05, 0.71])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.19, S.E. = 1.36, p = 0.889, 95% CI [-2.85, 2.47]; Std. beta = -0.05, 95% CI [-0.73, 0.64])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.94, S.E. = 0.82, p = 0.252, 95% CI [-2.56, 0.67]; Std. beta = -0.24, 95% CI [-0.66, 0.17])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 4.20, S.E. = 1.23, p < .001, 95% CI [1.79, 6.60]; Std. beta = 1.08, 95% CI [0.46, 1.70])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
